\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs32\b0\i0 Throughout the Bible}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s willingness to sacrifice Isaac represents the highest expression of his faith in Genesis. The authors of the }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\scaps nt}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  similarly recognized this event as a preeminent example of faithfully responding to God. The author of Hebrews emphasizes how Abraham serves as an example for believers, writing, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the one who received the promises was ready to offer his one and only son\u8221\'94 (Heb 11:17). The very tension we identified earlier is present here: While God\u8217\'92s command to sacrifice Isaac seemed to jeopardize God\u8217\'92s promise to him, Abraham \u8220\'93was ready.\u8221\'94 His example encourages us to \u8220\'93run with patient endurance the race that has been set before us\u8221\'94 (Heb 12:1).\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge21.1-21&off=16402"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 21:1\endash 22:24). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The authors of the }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\scaps nt}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  also believed Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s willingness to sacrifice Isaac foreshadowed the sacrifice of Jesus on the cross. Hebrews describes Isaac as Abraham\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93one and only son\u8221\'94 (Heb 11:17). The Greek term here, }{\f5\fs24\b0\i1 monogen\loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u275\'65s}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , is used most often in the }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\scaps nt}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  to describe Jesus, God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s only begotten Son (see John 1:14; 3:16). Paul also describes God\u8217\'92s sending of Christ to redeem humanity as \u8220\'93He did not spare His own Son\u8221\'94 (Rom 8:32), phrasing that echoes God\u8217\'92s words to Abraham in Gen 22:16.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 While the sacrifice of Isaac came to be understood as foreshadowing Christ\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s sacrifice, there was one major difference: Isaac was spared, whereas Christ was sacrificed. Abraham was willing to sacrifice his only son, but God intervened and provided a substitute for Isaac in the form of the ram (Gen 22:13). God loves us enough that He did not spare His only Son; instead, Christ took our place as }{\f5\fs24\b0\i1 our}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  substitute. And through the sacrifice of Christ, we have become heirs of the promise God first gave to Abraham and fulfilled through the redemption of Christ (Rom 8:17).}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs24\b0\i1 Study Questions}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\li360\fi-360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 1.\tab Read James 2:14\endash 26 and Rom 4:1\endash 25. How do you understand the interplay of faith and works as explained by James and Paul? What relevance does this have in your life?}
